  }))), "2.4. Typical workflow"), mdx("p", null, "Describing the current workflow in multidisciplinary UX/UI teams, the researchers characterised the current ASD process as \u201Cnot iterative enough\u201D (Jones, 2019). The disciplines of UX designer and UI developers are \u201Cdisjointed in their work and processes, which leads to inefficiencies\u201D (Jones, 2019). Jones and Thoma narrow down this problem to the fact that \u201Cagile decision- making at a localized level between designers and developers is a challenge in the organization\u201D (Jones and Thoma, 2019)."), mdx("p", null, "Trying to overcome these differences, both designers and developers experience a need to commit extra work. Thus, the previous studies mentioned that it takes a \u201Csurprising\u201D amount of time for the developers to recreate the design documents (Maudet et al., 2017).\nThe literature mentions that \u201Cmuch of the interaction time between these roles was used to re-align individual work progress to ensure a common understanding of the project aims\u201D (Jones, Thoma and Newell, 2016)."), mdx("p", null, "At the same time, there is a common understanding that UX/UI projects lack early communication between designers and developers, and that finds support in the scientific literature (Jones and Thoma, 2019)."), mdx("h5", {
